      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Here=E2=80=99s a puzzle for you:
=09On April 4, Elon Musk   signed an agreement=C2=A0saying that he would=C2=
=A0join the board of directors of Twitter Inc. and=C2=A0not make a hostile =
bid for Twitter. On April 9, five days later, Musk   decided not to join th=
e board of directors; by April 13, he   made a hostile bid for Twitter.=09O=
n April 25, Elon Musk   signed a merger agreement to buy Twitter for $54.20=
 per share in cash. On May 13, 18 days later,   Musk announced that the dea=
l was =E2=80=9Con hold,=E2=80=9D though it took him   until July 8 to forma=
lly tell Twitter that he was not going to buy it.=C2=A0=09Twitter sued in t=
he Delaware Court of Chancery, it was not going great for Musk, and the tri=
al was scheduled to start on Oct. 17. And this Monday, Oct. 3, Musk sent Tw=
itter  a letter saying that   he gives up and now plans to close the deal o=
n the original terms, paying $54.20 per share in cash. And then his lawyers=
=C2=A0filed a motion with the court asking the judge to stop the trial: =E2=
=80=9CClosing is expected on or around October 28,=E2=80=9D they wrote,=C2=
=A0so =E2=80=9Cthere is no need for an expedited trial to order Defendants =
to do what they are already doing and this action is now moot.=E2=80=9D  Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s lawyers objected; they don=E2=80=99t want to stop the trial=
 until they actually see Musk=E2=80=99s money.=09But yesterday evening the =
judge, Chancellor Kathaleen McCormick, agreed with Musk,  ruling: =E2=80=9C=
This action is stayed until 5 p.m. on October 28, 2022, to permit the parti=
es to close on the transaction. If the transaction does not close by 5 p.m.=
 on October 28, 2022, the parties are instructed to contact me by email tha=
t evening to obtain November 2022 trial dates.=E2=80=9D=09Musk changed his =
mind and agreed to close on Oct. 3. Oct. 28 is=C2=A0twenty-five days=C2=A0a=
fter that, and=C2=A0twenty-two days=C2=A0after the judge=E2=80=99s ruling y=
esterday. He backed out of his agreement to join the board in five days. He=
 changed his mind about his merger agreement in 18 days. No Elon Musk decis=
ion about Twitter has lasted three weeks without being reversed.=09What are=
 the odds that he changes his mind again before Oct. 28?

I don=E2=80=99t know! Let me make a few points. First: I think it is very, =
very likely that this deal will close by Oct. 28. Musk has generally been a=
 prankster in his dealings with Twitter, and his lawyers have to some exten=
t enabled him, but I do not think that they would sign up for pranking the =
judge=C2=A0in this case. If they are telling her that they expect to close =
by Oct. 28, and that =E2=80=9Ccounsel for the debt financing parties has ad=
vised that each of their clients is prepared to honor its obligations under=
 the Bank Debt Commitment Letter,=E2=80=9D then that=C2=A0probably=C2=A0mea=
ns that Musk=E2=80=99s debt financing is in place and that he plans to clos=
e by Oct. 28. If I were Twitter I=E2=80=99d want to move quickly before he =
changes his mind, but for this week anyway=C2=A0I assume he has made up his=
 mind to buy Twitter.
Second: I know nothing, I am constantly surprised by everything that happen=
s here, and when Musk says next week =E2=80=9Cguys, guys, did you know ther=
e are BOTS on Twitter? Deal=E2=80=99s off!=E2=80=9D I will be fine, I will =
be unsurprised, I have made my peace with it. I just want to flag that here=
 really clearly. If he bails again next week, you can email me and say =E2=
=80=9Chahaha you said the deal would probably close, you were so wrong,=E2=
=80=9D and I will say, yes, yes I was. And then we=E2=80=99ll do this some =
more. Won=E2=80=99t that be great.
Third, a sort of a sociological point, one that stereotypes far too broadly=
 but has some truth to it.=C2=A0There are two sorts of lawyers in the world=
,
  [2]
=C2=A0litigators=C2=A0and=C2=A0deal lawyers. Deal lawyers do things like ne=
gotiate merger agreements and debt financing, and make sure that all the fu=
nds flows and paperwork are right for the closings of those mergers and fin=
ancings. One part of their job is to think about how the other side might t=
ry to betray them, and write protections against that=C2=A0into the contrac=
t. But another big part of the job is to work with the other side in a coop=
erative way to make everyone happy, so that the deal moves smoothly and fee=
ls like, and is, a win for both sides. And then most of the time the deal c=
loses on schedule and everyone really is happy.
Every so often a deal goes wrong, and then the litigators come in to do the=
 lawsuit. The litigators are trying to=C2=A0win:=C2=A0When the deal has bec=
ome a lawsuit, the possible outcomes are much more zero-sum than they were =
when it was a deal. Litigators=C2=A0fight. The litigators for one side send=
 the other side discovery requests saying =E2=80=9Csend us all the document=
s you=E2=80=99ve written about this deal,=E2=80=9D and the litigators for t=
he other side send back objections saying =E2=80=9Cthis request is ridiculo=
us and we could never do that,=E2=80=9D and then they go to court and fight=
 bitterly about=C2=A0what documents they should send each other.=C2=A0That =
has been the main action in the Twitter case so far, arguing over documents=
 ahead of the trial, and it is the main action of much of modern US litigat=
ion, fighting over what documents you have to send to the other side. (Deal=
 lawyers love sending documents to the other side. The other side has to si=
gn them!)
When a deal turns into a bitter lawsuit the litigators take over, and the d=
eal lawyers go off and do something else. No deal lawyer is going to send a=
 closing memo to her counterpart on the other side in a lawsuit this bitter=
; the litigators would never allow it. What if the closing memo gives the o=
ther side some information? What if it tacitly admits something? No, the de=
al lawyers are too cooperative and conciliatory to be allowed near=C2=A0lit=
igation.
Most lawsuits settle, and when you negotiate a settlement you will want to =
have a good litigator on your side to say things like =E2=80=9Cif you don=
=E2=80=99t accept this settlement you will have to deal with me in court an=
d you won=E2=80=99t like that.=E2=80=9D But in this case, the settlement wi=
ll take the form of=C2=A0closing a merger. And to do that, you need the dea=
l lawyers to come back. You need them because they know the paperwork and f=
unds flows and incantations that are required=C2=A0to close a merger, but y=
ou also need them because of how they work. The deal lawyers on one side se=
nd a funds flow memo to the deal lawyers on the other side, and the deal la=
wyers on the other side send back a note that is like =E2=80=9Cthis looks g=
ood, thanks, but FYI we will have wires coming from two separate accounts, =
here they are,=E2=80=9D and the deal lawyers on the first side send back a =
note that is like =E2=80=9Cthanks, we=E2=80=99ve updated to reflect that.=
=E2=80=9D Litigators do not reply to discovery requests with notes that say=
 =E2=80=9Cthis looks good, thanks, but FYI you probably will want to read a=
 few other documents, we=E2=80=99ve added those.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The deep point of the stay in this case is to=C2=A0make the litigators go a=
way. They have been punching each other in the face for months, because tha=
t is their job and because they enjoy it, but now they have to stop, so the=
 deal lawyers can come back and actually close the deal. If you leave the l=
itigators in charge of the closing, they will litigate everything. =E2=80=
=9CWe really punched them in the face over this closing memo,=E2=80=9D they=
 will say as they high-five each other. And then it will never get done.
Fourth: If Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyers find themselves emailing Chancellor Mc=
Cormick at 5:00:01 p.m. on Oct. 28 to ask=C2=A0for a November trial date, s=
he=E2=80=99s gonna write back at 5:00:02 saying =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re doin=
g Nov.=C2=A01=C2=A0at 8 a.m.=E2=80=9D And the trial will be very quick, and=
 there will be a smell of brimstone in the courtroom, and Elon Musk had bet=
ter have a really really really really really really really really really g=
ood excuse for why he=E2=80=99s not closing. And that excuse had better be=
=C2=A0new. =E2=80=9CI think that as many as 6% of Twitter=E2=80=99s users m=
ight be bots=E2=80=9D is not gonna cut it.=C2=A0
Fifth: The most obvious=C2=A0excuse =E2=80=94=C2=A0the sticking point that =
people seem to be worried about here =E2=80=94=C2=A0is Musk=E2=80=99s debt =
financing. Musk=E2=80=99s  motion to postpone the trial foreshadows this a =
bit:
If the Debt Financing does not fund, Twitter may not obtain an order of spe=
cific performance under Section 9.9(b) causing Musk to fund the equity or c=
lose the transaction. The Merger Agreement, which Twitter is seeking to enf=
orce at trial, unambiguously prohibits any court-ordered closing based on s=
pecific performance absent funding of the debt.=C2=A0The absence of any bas=
is for specific performance in that scenario knocks the props out from unde=
r the original application for expedited proceedings, warranting adjournmen=
t of the October 17 trial date. And, of course,=C2=A0if the debt does fund,=
 as Defendants fully expect, then the transaction will close, entirely moot=
ing the need for specific performance.
That is, if Musk=E2=80=99s banks don=E2=80=99t fund their $13 billion debt =
commitment, Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers say, then the court could not order Musk=
 to close the deal, and he=E2=80=99d only have to pay a $1 billion reverse =
termination fee.
  [3]

This is, to be clear, a correct reading of the merger agreement; we=E2=80=
=99ve been   talking about it since   April. It is not the end of the story=
: The court could order Musk to=C2=A0sue=C2=A0the banks to make them fund.
  [4]
=C2=A0And if the banks do not fund=C2=A0because=C2=A0Musk intentionally ble=
w up the financing, then there is   some precedent (from Chancellor McCormi=
ck) for the court to just tell Musk =E2=80=9Clook, whatever the merger agre=
ement may say, you have to close, so you=E2=80=99d better come up with $46=
=C2=A0billion.=E2=80=9D And just generally if Musk shows up in court again =
in three weeks saying =E2=80=9Cwell, I know that I=C2=A0said=C2=A0that the =
debt financing would come through,=C2=A0and you stopped the trial because o=
f that, but it turns out I was wrong, oh well, deal=E2=80=99s off,=E2=80=9D=
 then the judge is not going to be the least bit amused.
Of course=C2=A0I=C2=A0will be amused; I   wrote on Wednesday:
There are=C2=A0funny possibilities here. Maybe everyone will show up at the=
 closing and Morgan Stanley will walk in and say =E2=80=9Chey guys you=E2=
=80=99re not going to believe this but we have reason to think that more th=
an 5% of Twitter=E2=80=99s users are spam bots, which would create a materi=
al adverse effect on the company, so we can=E2=80=99t close the financing,=
=C2=A0deal=E2=80=99s off.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That would be the funniest possible=
 outcome, much funnier than Musk just changing his mind again.=C2=A0Musk is=
 a business prankster and his antics are getting old, but for a serious Mor=
gan Stanley banker to show up and do the bot routine, with a straight face,=
=C2=A0would be incredible.
But I think the chances of this are slim. In general, it is very bad form f=
or banks to try to back out of their debt financing commitments, to the poi=
nt that it almost never happens. Musk=E2=80=99s banks are going to lose at =
least hundreds of millions of dollars selling this debt on the terms they a=
greed to in happier times in April, but that   happens all the time; banks =
don=E2=80=99t try to get out of buyout financing commitments just because t=
he market has shifted and they=E2=80=99ll lose huge amounts of money. This =
is in part for reasons of reputation, but also=C2=A0the contracts are writt=
en that way:=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s  debt=C2=A0commitment letters, as is stand=
ard, give his banks almost no excuses to get out of the deal.=C2=A0
Even beyond those general points, there are the specifics of this deal. Mus=
k has  told the judge that =E2=80=9Cthe Debt Financing parties have indicat=
ed that they are prepared to honor their commitments=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C=
are working cooperatively to fund the close.=E2=80=9D It would be=C2=A0hard=
 for the banks to walk back on that. And everyone knows =E2=80=94=C2=A0I=E2=
=80=99ve been saying it for months, and now Musk is more or less admitting =
it =E2=80=94=C2=A0that Musk=E2=80=99s arguments for getting out of the deal=
 were ridiculous, so it would be ridiculous for the banks to try them. They=
 will swallow hard and put up the money.
That said, it will take them some time. Musk=E2=80=99s motion says:
Defendants are working diligently, cooperatively, and in good faith with th=
e financing banks to prepare for the closing. That funding, however, will t=
ake time because the parties are working through the complex process of arr=
anging $12.5 billion dollars of debt financing, including drafting required=
 documentation, arranging security interests for a portion of the debt fina=
ncing, and finalizing funding mechanics. Understandably, that cannot happen=
 before the October 17 trial.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 Counsel for the financing bank=
s have estimated they will need until October 28 to fund the loans.
That=E2=80=99s kind of weird? In a perfect world, the banks would do two br=
oad sorts of things before funding this deal:
=09Paperwork, and=09Sell most of the debt to investors rather than funding =
it themselves.

Everything mentioned in Musk=E2=80=99s motion =E2=80=94=C2=A0drafting, secu=
rity interests, funding mechanics =E2=80=94 is in the first category, paper=
work, and for enough money you can do any amount of paperwork in a week by =
ruining some lawyers=E2=80=99 personal lives. I don=E2=80=99t know why it w=
ould take until Oct. 28.
On the other hand Musk=E2=80=99s motion does=C2=A0not=C2=A0say that the ban=
ks plan to=C2=A0market=C2=A0the debt to investors before the closing, and, =
as we   discussed on Wednesday, they have to fund the debt (with their own =
money) even if they don=E2=80=99t have a chance to=C2=A0market it first. An=
d selling this debt =E2=80=94=C2=A0doing the paperwork, getting Twitter and=
 Musk to work together on=C2=A0marketing materials, holding meetings with i=
nvestors, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0in three weeks would be awfully aggressive. =
=E2=80=9CThe banks, including Bank of America, Barclays, and Japanese bank =
and Morgan Stanley-investor MUFG, are not expected to attempt to raise $12.=
5bn of the debt through public or private debt markets before the takeover =
is finalised, as is usually the case in a leveraged buyout,=E2=80=9D says  =
the Financial Times. The banks plan to bridge this debt themselves (and the=
n try to sell it later, after closing).
So I don=E2=80=99t quite know why it would take three weeks for them to fin=
d the money. They=E2=80=99re banks, they have lots of money. In  their resp=
onse to Musk=E2=80=99s motion yesterday, Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyers said:
Nor have they supplied any reason to believe that closing cannot be achieve=
d in the days before trial. Just this morning, a corporate representative f=
or one of the lending banks testified that Mr. Musk has yet to send them a =
borrowing notice and has not otherwise communicated to them that he intends=
 to close the transaction, let alone on any particular timeline. The bank f=
urther testified that the main task necessary to close the deal=E2=80=94mem=
orializing the debt financing=E2=80=94could have happened in July but didn=
=E2=80=99t because Mr. Musk purported to terminate the deal.
I think it is probably a=C2=A0little=C2=A0cute for Twitter to say that Musk=
=E2=80=99s banks haven=E2=80=99t yet put up the money because he hasn=E2=80=
=99t yet asked them to, but the timeline is a little weird.
If Elon Musk walked into=C2=A0court and handed Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyers a =
sack full of $46=C2=A0billion in cash, that would not be quite sufficient t=
o close this deal, but it would be pretty close. There=E2=80=99d be some pa=
perwork, some filings, some administrative work left to do; it would take a=
 few days of lawyers=E2=80=99 time. But practically speaking if he put up t=
he $46 billion this would be over. He=E2=80=99s the richest person in the w=
orld and can surely get together his $33 billion portion of it.
  [5]
 His banks are really big banks, and can surely get together their $13 bill=
ion portion. Again, might take a few days, some paperwork, but that is the =
business they have chosen; you can=E2=80=99t really go around being like =
=E2=80=9CI promise Morgan Stanley will give me $13 billion but we need to w=
ait until it gets its paycheck at the end of the month.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
So when Musk told Twitter that he wants to call off the lawsuit and close t=
he merger, Twitter understandably said, yes, right, show us the $46 billion=
 and we=E2=80=99ll get right on that. And Musk said, no, let=E2=80=99s call=
 off the lawsuit first, and then you=E2=80=99ll get your money by the end o=
f the month. I don=E2=80=99t think that Musk was=C2=A0wrong=C2=A0to ask for=
 that; I think that calling off the lawsuit probably=C2=A0will=C2=A0make th=
e closing easier and smoother and more pleasant and possibly even faster. I=
 can see why the judge granted Musk=E2=80=99s request. But I can also see w=
hy Twitter is nervous. Twitter would be happier if it could see the money. =
And Musk changes his mind a lot.

