<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know! Let me make a few points=
. First: I think it is very, very likely that this deal will close by Oct. =
28. Musk has generally been a prankster in his dealings with Twitter, and h=
is lawyers have to some extent enabled him, but I do not think that they wo=
uld sign up for pranking the <em>judge=C2=A0</em>in this case. If they are =
telling her that they expect to close by Oct. 28, and that =E2=80=9Ccounsel=
 for the debt financing parties has advised that each of their clients is p=
repared to honor its obligations under the Bank Debt Commitment Letter,=E2=
=80=9D then that=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=A0</em>means that Musk=E2=80=99s debt=
 financing is in place and that he plans to close by Oct. 28. If I were Twi=
tter I=E2=80=99d want to move quickly before he changes his mind, but for t=
his week anyway=C2=A0I assume he has made up his mind to buy Twitter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second: I know nothing, I am constantly surpri=
sed by everything that happens here, and when Musk says next week =E2=80=9C=
guys, guys, did you know there are BOTS on Twitter? Deal=E2=80=99s off!=E2=
=80=9D I will be fine, I will be unsurprised, I have made my peace with it.=
 I just want to flag that here really clearly. If he bails again next week,=
 you can email me and say =E2=80=9Chahaha you said the deal would probably =
close, you were so wrong,=E2=80=9D and I will say, yes, yes I was. And then=
 we=E2=80=99ll do this some more. Won=E2=80=99t that be great.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third, a sort of a sociological point, one tha=
t stereotypes far too broadly but has some truth to it.=C2=A0There are two =
sorts of lawyers in the world,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0<em>litigators=C2=A0</em>and=C2=A0<em>deal lawyers</em>. Deal law=
yers do things like negotiate merger agreements and debt financing, and mak=
e sure that all the funds flows and paperwork are right for the closings of=
 those mergers and financings. One part of their job is to think about how =
the other side might try to betray them, and write protections against that=
=C2=A0into the contract. But another big part of the job is to work with th=
e other side in a cooperative way to make everyone happy, so that the deal =
moves smoothly and feels like, and is, a win for both sides. And then most =
of the time the deal closes on schedule and everyone really is happy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every so often a deal goes wrong, and then the=
 litigators come in to do the lawsuit. The litigators are trying to=C2=A0<e=
m>win:=C2=A0</em>When the deal has become a lawsuit, the possible outcomes =
are much more zero-sum than they were when it was a deal. Litigators=C2=A0<=
em>fight</em>. The litigators for one side send the other side discovery re=
quests saying =E2=80=9Csend us all the documents you=E2=80=99ve written abo=
ut this deal,=E2=80=9D and the litigators for the other side send back obje=
ctions saying =E2=80=9Cthis request is ridiculous and we could never do tha=
t,=E2=80=9D and then they go to court and fight bitterly about=C2=A0<em>wha=
t documents they should send each other.=C2=A0</em>That has been the main a=
ction in the Twitter case so far, arguing over documents ahead of the trial=
, and it is the main action of much of modern US litigation, fighting over =
what documents you have to send to the other side. (Deal lawyers love sendi=
ng documents to the other side. The other side has to sign them!)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When a deal turns into a bitter lawsuit the li=
tigators take over, and the deal lawyers go off and do something else. No d=
eal lawyer is going to send a closing memo to her counterpart on the other =
side in a lawsuit this bitter; the litigators would never allow it. What if=
 the closing memo gives the other side some information? What if it tacitly=
 admits something? No, the deal lawyers are too cooperative and conciliator=
y to be allowed near=C2=A0litigation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most lawsuits settle, and when you negotiate a=
 settlement you will want to have a good litigator on your side to say thin=
gs like =E2=80=9Cif you don=E2=80=99t accept this settlement you will have =
to deal with me in court and you won=E2=80=99t like that.=E2=80=9D But in t=
his case, the settlement will take the form of=C2=A0<em>closing a merger</e=
m>. And to do that, you need the deal lawyers to come back. You need them b=
ecause they know the paperwork and funds flows and incantations that are re=
quired=C2=A0to close a merger, but you also need them because of <em>how</e=
m> they work. The deal lawyers on one side send a funds flow memo to the de=
al lawyers on the other side, and the deal lawyers on the other side send b=
ack a note that is like =E2=80=9Cthis looks good, thanks, but FYI we will h=
ave wires coming from two separate accounts, here they are,=E2=80=9D and th=
e deal lawyers on the first side send back a note that is like =E2=80=9Ctha=
nks, we=E2=80=99ve updated to reflect that.=E2=80=9D Litigators do not repl=
y to discovery requests with notes that say =E2=80=9Cthis looks good, thank=
s, but FYI you probably will want to read a few other documents, we=E2=80=
=99ve added those.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deep point of the stay in this case is to=
=C2=A0<em>make the litigators go away</em>. They have been punching each ot=
her in the face for months, because that is their job and because they enjo=
y it, but now they have to stop, so the deal lawyers can come back and actu=
ally close the deal. If you leave the litigators in charge of the closing, =
they will litigate everything. =E2=80=9CWe really punched them in the face =
over this closing memo,=E2=80=9D they will say as they high-five each other=
. And then it will never get done.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fourth: If Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyers find them=
selves emailing Chancellor McCormick at 5:00:01 p.m. on Oct. 28 to ask=C2=
=A0for a November trial date, she=E2=80=99s gonna write back at 5:00:02 say=
ing =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re doing Nov.=C2=A01=C2=A0at 8 a.m.=E2=80=9D And th=
e trial will be very quick, and there will be a smell of brimstone in the c=
ourtroom, and Elon Musk had better have a really really really really reall=
y really really really really good excuse for why he=E2=80=99s not closing.=
 And that excuse had better be=C2=A0<em>new</em>. =E2=80=9CI think that as =
many as 6% of Twitter=E2=80=99s users might be bots=E2=80=9D is not gonna c=
ut it.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fifth: The most obvious=C2=A0excuse =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the sticking point that people seem to be worried about here =E2=80=
